				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/boogey-man23" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2362395); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2362395&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183421" alt="Boogey_Man23" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2362395)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/boogey-man23" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2362395); return false;" >Boogey_Man23</a></span> <span class="odate time_1590724678 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 May 2020 03:57</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4667590">
									

<p>One of the things I picked up on when analysing the original SCP-106 in preparation for this was an almost gratuitous use of &quot;terms in quotes&quot; there (sometimes working to ominous effect, but sometimes&#8230; not so much (which I thought was a bit funny in itself)).</p>
<p>So in turn, I peppered them into this piece - perhaps gratuitously. Some of them may be subversions of lines from the original article, some of them may be that line of thinking extending into the rest of the writing.</p>
<p>I will give some thought as to whether all of them necessarily contribute to a gag or punchline, or maybe could stand to be replaced with more typical/clinical wording. Thank you for your comment!</p>

